Still here,<br><br>
Guys!   I was out of town all day, Friday, looking at a college for my daughter.  Ed, I believe, Pack Mom loves me best.  However, if you want the role of  being Mom's favorite -- go right ahead.  Now, that I have expressed my generiosity to MTF,  I  move onward and upward out of a smaller world where tunnel vision is a necessity.<br><br>
This is difficult -- the question of the draft.  I'm sure that all of us couldn't count the times that little kids (ours and others)  have uttered the words &quot;that's not fair.&quot;  I (we) try to treat them fairly at the same time telling them that is really not fair, although we wish it was.<br><br>
The draft was not fair -- equal -- because of the deferrments.  My brother went to college for 3 years and then quit and joined the army.  He spent one year over seas and came home and finished his college education.<br><br>
Feelings of abandonment and betrayal regarding the draft, service and non service are life long for many.  We are all &quot;marked&quot; with our choices -- whether they are feelings of pride and/or regret.  Conscience doesn't ask that we all agree or act the same.  It does ask that that we be honest to our values.<br><br>
The sad part of &quot;all of this&quot; was the race for the moral high ground.  The lives of the South Vietnamese, our allies, after the war reaches deep into my soul.  We all &quot;knew&quot; that the North Vietnamese didn't abide by the Peace Accord in January 1973 should not come as a great shock to anyone -- that was inevitable.  That the US Congress stopped the money that was promised to the South Vietnamese governement during the next two years is, again, sad.  Talk about betrayal!  How much &quot;good PR&quot; did the South Vietnamse receive in all of this.  They deserved better.<br><br>
Someone wrote on one these threads that he never saw anyone walking north to live in Hanoi.  There was never given a great deal of sympathy for the boat people who left after 1975.  Everyone was tired -- and the southerners paid the biggest price.<br><br>
People turning the heads can be called the history of the world.  I'm sure many of you remember Kitty Genevese is New York City, who was murdered and no one came to her rescue.  Individuals who answer the call to conscience and be called &quot;real heroes&quot; but they are not.  Personally, I do not believe in heroes.  I do believe in people who &quot;just did their jobs&quot; but there is something inside them for most days in their lives COULD NOT HAVE ACTED DIFFERENTLY.  They have my respect.<br><br>
Paul<br><br>
